European Union doubles its trade with India
As the European Union and India are reciprocal trading partners, this issue, in addition to the other largely global issues, dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A Franco-Indian summit will also be held today to focus on nuclear energy cooperation.
Although the European Union recognizes that India is a great developing democratic power that should have more voice and vote in international affairs, member countries have not yet been able to reach a common denominator on whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue has not been addressed at the ninth summit that began yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, EU President José Manuel Barroso, Commission President, and Javier Solana, India’s prime minister, welcomed Manmohan Singh, with whom they reached an agreement to double in five years, i.e. increase to more than one hundred billion euros, their trade exchange.
